Instead of focusing the protocol around dictionaries, do it around `Config` instances because conversion to dictionary is specific to the format -- ConfigParser needs everything as string-representations, JSON probably can handle the raw value, YAML -- not sure.
```
def dump_config_to_file(config, file_obj, **kwargs)
def dump_config_to_string(config, **kwargs)
def load_config_from_file(file_obj, **kwargs)
def load_config_from_string(string, **kwargs)
```

I am working on making an audio player skill with flask ask using the built-in MusicGroup Intents referenced here https://developer.amazon.com/docs/custom-skills/musicgroup-intents.html#musicgroup-slots

according to this documentation and my tests, the intent "AMAZON.SearchAction<object@MusicGroup>" has a slot named "object.name" which I am trying to bring into my function however I am unable to because if I include the dot in the function's parameter it results in a syntax error.  if I exclude the . and just use objectname it appears empty and returns "None" instead of the input.  I'll provide some excerpts of my code and the JSON

is there some way to capture this slot into a variable or is formatting of the built-in slot with the dot going to make it impossible? 

flask ask python code:
`@ask.intent("AMAZON.SearchAction<object@MusicGroup>")
def play_artist(objectname):
    speech_text = "I will play %s" % objectname
    return statement(speech_text)
`

json request:
` "request": {
    "type": "IntentRequest",
    "requestId": "EdwRequestId.******",
    "intent": {
      "name": "AMAZON.SearchAction<object@MusicGroup>",
      "slots": {
        "object.name": {
          "name": "object.name",
          "value": "black sabbath"
        }
      }
    },
 `

json response:
`{
  "version": "1.0",
  "response": {
    "outputSpeech": {
      "text": "I will play None",
      "type": "PlainText"
    },
    "speechletResponse": {
      "outputSpeech": {
        "text": "I will play None"
      },
      "shouldEndSession": true
    }
  },
  "sessionAttributes": {}
}`

I notice that if a try to protect an entire blueprint with `@jwt_required`, than also the `OPTIONS` method is protected. 

`OPTIONS` method should not include crendetials, see [here](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/15734031/why-does-the-preflight-options-request-of-an-authenticated-cors-request-work-in).

The `@jwt_required` decorator should ignore `OPTIONS` like in `flask_login`:


````python
    @wraps(func)
    def decorated_view(*args, **kwargs):
        if request.method in EXEMPT_METHODS:
            return func(*args, **kwargs)
        elif current_app.login_manager._login_disabled:
            return func(*args, **kwargs)
        elif not current_user.is_authenticated:
            return current_app.login_manager.unauthorized()
        return func(*args, **kwargs)
    return decorated_view
```

where `EXEMPT_METHODS=set(["OPTIONS"])`!

I should fix this and create a pull request if this is not a desired choice!

I am trying to understand the valid values for the illumination and contrast image augmentation parameters but the docs are quite succint.  A value of zero means no change but what are the reasonable range of values that I can use?
I tried looking at the code and the relevant section seems to be in src/io/iter_normalize.h (copied bellow) but I get confused by the rand_uniform(rnd_) and I fail to understand the valid ranges of contrast and illumination.

```
outimg_.Resize(data.shape_);
    float contrast =
        rand_uniform(rnd_) * param_.max_random_contrast * 2 - param_.max_random_contrast + 1;
    float illumination =
        rand_uniform(rnd_) * param_.max_random_illumination * 2 - param_.max_random_illumination;

    if (param_.mean_r > 0.0f || param_.mean_g > 0.0f ||
        param_.mean_b > 0.0f || param_.mean_a > 0.0f) {
      // subtract mean per channel                                                                                                                                              
      data[0] -= param_.mean_r;
      if (data.shape_[0] >= 3) {
        data[1] -= param_.mean_g;
        data[2] -= param_.mean_b;
      }
      if (data.shape_[0] == 4) {
        data[3] -= param_.mean_a;
      }
      if ((param_.rand_mirror && coin_flip(rnd_)) || param_.mirror) {
        outimg_ = mirror(data * contrast + illumination) * param_.scale;
      } else {
        outimg_ = (data * contrast + illumination) * param_.scale;
      }

```

I want to ask if exists a better way, how to create filter query.
```python
search = Search()

# I have query_string query which I want use inside a filter phrase
my_query = query.Q('query_string', query='complex query...')

# this command failure
my_filter_search = search.filter('query', my_query)

#this works in python but, elasticsearch return SearchPhaseExecutionException[Failed to execute phase [query]...
my_filter_search = search.filter('query', query=my_query)
# output is
# "filter": {
#     "query": {
#         "query": {
#             "query_string": {
#                 "query": "complex query..."
#             }
#         }
#     }
# }

# this works ok, but is it the right way?
my_filter_search = search.filter('query', **my_query.to_dict()) 
# output is
# "filter": {
#     "query": {
#         "query_string": {
#             "query": "complex query..."
#         }
#     }
# }
```

