Hello everyone.
I have a little issue with post_load, can someone help me?
Before that look at the next example:

```
from typing import List, Optional

from marshmallow import Schema, fields, post_load


class DomainItemsIds:
    def __init__(self, items: List[int]):
        self.items = items


class DomainOrder:
    def __init__(self, order: Optional[DomainItemsIds]):
        self.order = order


class DomainItemsIdsSchema(Schema):
    items = fields.List(fields.Integer())

    @post_load
    def make(self, data: dict) -> Optional[DomainItemsIds]:
        items = data['items']

        if len(items) == 0:
            return None
        else:
            return DomainItemsIds(items)


class DomainOrderSchema(Schema):
    order = fields.Nested(DomainItemsIdsSchema, many=False, allow_none=True)

    @post_load
    def make(self, data: dict) -> DomainOrder:
        return DomainOrder(data.get('order'))


s = DomainOrderSchema()
r = s.load({'order': {'items': []}}).data
r.order == {'items': []}
```

So, after post_load I have received the dict of {'items': []}.
If I clearly understand logic, I should see None.
What I did incorrectly in this example?

Hi,

I have the following code:

```python
import graphene

class OptionBase(graphene.Interface):
    id = graphene.ID()
    name = graphene.String()

class Option(graphene.ObjectType):
    class Meta:
        interfaces = (OptionBase,)
    pass

class CategoryOption(graphene.ObjectType):
    class Meta:
        interfaces = (OptionBase,)
    special_field1 = graphene.Int()

class OptionCollection(graphene.ObjectType):
    name = graphene.String()
    opts = graphene.List(OptionBase)

class OptionType(graphene.Enum):
    SOME_TYPE1 = 'Type_1'
    SOME_TYPE2 = 'Type_2'

class Query(graphene.ObjectType):
    options = graphene.List(OptionCollection, option_types=graphene.List(OptionType), required=True)

    def resolve_options(self, args, context, info):
        option_by_type = OptionCollection(name='Test Collection')
        option_by_type.opts = [Option(id=1, name='Display'), Option(id=2, name='Video')]
        return [option_by_type]

schema = graphene.Schema(query=Query)

q = """
{options(optionTypes: [SOME_TYPE1]) {
   name
   opts {
     name
   }
}
}
"""
result = schema.execute(q)
print result.errors
```

All I get is:

[AttributeError("'NoneType' object has no attribute 'graphene_type'",), AttributeError("'NoneType' object has no attribute 'graphene_type'",)]

If I print the schema, I get:

```
schema {
  query: Query
}

interface OptionBase {
  id: ID
  name: String
}

type OptionCollection {
  name: String
  opts: [OptionBase]
}

enum OptionType {
  SOME_TYPE1
  SOME_TYPE2
}

type Query {
  options(optionTypes: [OptionType]): [OptionCollection]!
}
```

So, types Option and CategoryOption are gone. Any idea about this? Might be my error since I am new to GraphQL and Graphene.

Thank you.

I am trying to upgrade to 2.x but new template magic leads to incomprehensible template error stacks: `Unknown/invalid class_ template parameters provided`.
 This seems to have been introduced in 5fffe200e337f1a1bb13034fac29a63ad6eae304.

I have 2 issues with this:

1. I am puzzled whether this really is the user experience that pybind11 wants to provide to users. The error message conveys near zero information. I am wondering whether this code has been reviewed?

2. Also the new `class_` API is not well documented.
  There seems to be no description what the upgrade path from the old API is or what traits the new API awaits.

As a result, can someone explain what the upgrade path for the following code from:

    void bindMyResource(py::module& m) {
        py::class_<MyResource, IntrusivePtr<MyResource>>(m, "Model", py::base<Resource>);
    }

to:

    void bindMyResource(py::module& m) {
        py::class_<MyResource, IntrusivePtr<MyResource>>(m, "Model", /*probably some type that gets passed in here*/);
    }

or:

    void bindMyResource(py::module& m) {
        py::class_<MyResource, Resource, IntrusivePtr<MyResource>>(m, "Model");
    }

is? Thanks.

Installing in Windows crashes in setup.py

> python setup.py install
at Microsoft Visual Studio 9.0\VC\BIN\cl.exe ...
pygit2.c(496) : error C2275: 'PyObject' : illegal use of this type as an expression

Error is caused by variable declaration in the middle of the method in Repository_read;

Fix is to move the declaration to the beginning of the method

    static PyObject *
    Repository_read(Repository *self, PyObject *py_hex)
    {
        git_oid oid;
        int err;
        git_odb_object *obj;
        size_t len;
        PyObject* tuple; // add declaration in line 487

    ...

        tuple = Py_BuildValue( // Remove tuple declaration in line 497
